Fix AOT-incompatible JSON calls in these files under `/tmp/sv-272064a0deed43f88f2b78f1731aecd8/before/`.

## File 1: `Common/Custom/Models/ManagedServiceIdentity.Serialization.cs`

Line 31: `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType, jOptions);`
The `ManagedServiceIdentityTypeConverter.Write` does: `writer.WritePropertyName("type"); writer.WriteStringValue(model.ToString());`
So replace `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType, jOptions);` with:
```csharp
writer.WritePropertyName("type"u8);
                writer.WriteStringValue(ManagedServiceIdentityType.ToString());
```

Line 49: `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, item.Value, jOptions);` where item.Value is `UserAssignedIdentity`
Replace with: `writer.WriteObjectValue(item.Value, ModelSerializationExtensions.WireOptions);`

Line 206: `type = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<ManagedServiceIdentityType>($"{{{property}}}");`
The `ManagedServiceIdentityTypeConverter.Read` reads a JSON object `{"type":"value"}` and returns `new ManagedServiceIdentityType(property.Value.GetString())`.
Replace with: `type = new ManagedServiceIdentityType(property.Value.GetString());`

Line 218: `dictionary.Add(new ResourceIdentifier(property0.Name), JsonSerializer.Deserialize<UserAssignedIdentity>(property0.Value.GetRawText()));`
The `UserAssignedIdentityConverter.Read` parses the JSON and calls `DeserializeUserAssignedIdentity(element)`.
Replace with: `dictionary.Add(new ResourceIdentifier(property0.Name), UserAssignedIdentity.DeserializeUserAssignedIdentity(property0.Value));`

## File 2: `ManagementGroup/Generated/LongRunningOperation/ManagementGroupsArmOperation.cs`
Line 61: `var lroDetails = ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default).ToObjectFromJson<Dictionary<string, string>>();`
`ToObjectFromJson<T>()` uses `JsonSerializer.Deserialize<T>` internally and is not AOT-safe.
Replace with manual JSON parsing:
```csharp
var binaryData = ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default);
            using var doc = JsonDocument.Parse(binaryData);
            var lroDetails = new Dictionary<string, string>();
            foreach (var prop in doc.RootElement.EnumerateObject())
            {
                lroDetails[prop.Name] = prop.Value.GetString();
            }
```
Make sure to add `using System.Text.Json;` if not already present.

## File 3: `ManagementGroup/Generated/LongRunningOperation/ManagementGroupsArmOperationOfT.cs`
Same fix as File 2 on line 61.

## File 4: `Resources/Generated/LongRunningOperation/ResourcesArmOperation.cs`
Same fix as File 2 on line 61.

## File 5: `Resources/Generated/LongRunningOperation/ResourcesArmOperationOfT.cs`
Same fix as File 2 on line 61.

## File 6: `ArmEnvironment.cs`
Line 80: `public override string ToString() => JsonSerializer.Serialize(this);`
ArmEnvironment is a simple struct with Endpoint (Uri) and Audience (string) properties. Replace with manual string construction:
```csharp
public override string ToString() => $"{{\"Endpoint\":\"{Endpoint}\",\"Audience\":\"{Audience}\"}}";
```
Wait, but the original uses JsonSerializer which would produce properly escaped JSON. The struct only has simple string/Uri properties so manual construction is safe. However, let me match the existing behavior: `JsonSerializer.Serialize(this)` would produce JSON using camelCase or the default property naming. Actually, looking at the struct, `Endpoint` is a `Uri` and `Audience` is a `string` and `DefaultScope` is a computed `string`. The default `System.Text.Json` serialization would include all public properties with their original names.

A cleaner approach: use `JsonSerializer.Serialize` with a source-generated context. Create a `JsonSerializerContext` or use manual Utf8JsonWriter:
```csharp
public override string ToString()
{
    using var stream = new System.IO.MemoryStream();
    using var writer = new Utf8JsonWriter(stream);
    writer.WriteStartObject();
    writer.WriteString("Endpoint"u8, Endpoint.ToString());
    writer.WriteString("Audience"u8, Audience);
    writer.WriteString("DefaultScope"u8, DefaultScope);
    writer.WriteEndObject();
    writer.Flush();
    return System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(stream.ToArray());
}
```

Actually, this is getting complex. A simpler approach: just use string interpolation for this simple struct. But we need to ensure it matches the JSON output format. Let me use Utf8JsonWriter.

## File 7: `ArmClientOptions.cs`
Line 52: `var allProfile = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>>(span);`
Replace with manual `JsonDocument.Parse` and navigation:
```csharp
using var document = JsonDocument.Parse(span);
var allProfile = new Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>();
foreach (var ns in document.RootElement.EnumerateObject())
{
    var inner = new Dictionary<string, JsonElement>();
    foreach (var apiVersion in ns.Value.EnumerateObject())
    {
        inner[apiVersion.Name] = apiVersion.Value.Clone();
    }
    allProfile[ns.Name] = inner;
}
```
IMPORTANT: Note that `document` is disposed at the end of the `using` block, so any `JsonElement` values from `document.RootElement` will become invalid. We need to `.Clone()` any JsonElement values we keep.

Wait actually, looking at the existing code more carefully:
```csharp
var allProfile = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>>(span);
var armProfile = allProfile["resource-manager"];
foreach (var keyValuePair in armProfile)
{
    var namespaceName = keyValuePair.Key;
    var element = keyValuePair.Value;
    foreach (var apiVersionProperty in element.EnumerateObject())
    {
        ...
    }
}
```

The `element` is a `JsonElement` that's iterated. After deserialization, the JsonElements are self-contained (backed by the parsed document), so they're fine.

If we use `JsonDocument.Parse`, we need the document to remain alive while we iterate. Since the entire iteration happens within the same method, we can use `using var document = JsonDocument.Parse(span);` and then navigate directly:

```csharp
using var profileDoc = JsonDocument.Parse(span);
var armProfile = profileDoc.RootElement.GetProperty("resource-manager");
foreach (var keyValuePair in armProfile.EnumerateObject())
{
    var namespaceName = keyValuePair.Name;
    var element = keyValuePair.Value;
    foreach (var apiVersionProperty in element.EnumerateObject())
    {
        ... (rest stays the same)
    }
}
```

This is much simpler! We skip the intermediate Dictionary entirely and navigate the JSON directly.

